<fr:p><fr:strong>Base case:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=1]]></fr:tex>. We see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{1}(x)=x-1]]></fr:tex> is clearly irreducible.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Inductive hypothesis:</fr:strong> Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{d}(x)\in \mathbb {Z}[x]]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d<n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Inductive case:</fr:strong> We see
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)f(x)=x^{n}-1]]></fr:tex>
where
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[f(x)=\prod _{d\mathrel {\bigm |} n}\Phi _{d}(x)\in \mathbb {Z}[x]]]></fr:tex>
by the inductive hypothesis. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{n}-1=f(x)\Phi _{n}(x)]]></fr:tex> is a factorization over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>. But by <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-002U.xml"
addr="ra-002U"
title="Factorization of formal polynomials with coefficients in UFDs">Gauss's lemma</fr:link>, since both <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)]]></fr:tex> are monic, we see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)\in \mathbb {Z}[x]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
