title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 2:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)]]></fr:tex> is irreducible. Suppose we have some factorization
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)=f(x)g(x)]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)\in \mathbb {Z}[x]]]></fr:tex> is irreducible and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)\in \mathbb {Z}[x]]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\zeta ]]></fr:tex> be a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\zeta \in \mu _{n}]]></fr:tex> primitive.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We claim: for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is coprime to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\zeta ^{a}]]></fr:tex> is a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>. It suffices to prove this for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a=p]]></fr:tex> prime. We have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(\zeta ^{p})=0]]></fr:tex> imply either <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(\zeta ^{p})=0]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(\zeta ^{p})=0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Subcase 1:</fr:strong> Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(\zeta ^{p})=0]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\zeta ]]></fr:tex> is a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g(x)]]></fr:tex>, but <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\zeta ]]></fr:tex> is a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> <fr:em>and</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> is irreducible. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)\mathrel {\bigm |} g(x^{p})]]></fr:tex>. Using the surjective map
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {split}\mathbb {Z}[x]\to \mathbb {F}_{p}[x]\\ f(x)\mapsto \overline {f}(x)\end {split}]]></fr:tex>
we see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)\mathrel {\bigm |} g(x^{p})]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}(x)\mathrel {\bigm |}\overline {g}(x^{p})]]></fr:tex>, but we see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {g}(x^{p})=\overline {g}(x)^{p}]]></fr:tex>. This implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {g}]]></fr:tex> share a common root, which contradicts the irreducibility of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{n}-1]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}_{p}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Subcase 2:</fr:strong> Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(\zeta ^{p})=0]]></fr:tex>. Then for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is coprime with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\zeta ^{a}]]></fr:tex> is a root of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex>. This implies
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)\mathrel {\bigm |} f(x),]]></fr:tex>
which means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)=f(x)]]></fr:tex>. Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi _{n}(x)]]></fr:tex> is irreducible.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
